{
  "texts": [
    "There is a one-to-one correspondence between:(i) Invariant, symmetric (0, 2)-tensors on the vertical distributionV of M = B × ρ N; (ii) Sections of Sym 2 (adM); (iii) ρ-equivariant maps s: B → Sym 2 (𝔫 *): (11) s(b • γ) = ρ(γ -1) • s(b), γ ∈ π 1 (B), b ∈ B.The action of π 1 (B) on Sym 2 (𝔫 *) is obtained from composing ρ: π 1 (B) → Aut(𝔫) ⊂ GL(𝔫) with the natural extension of the standard GL(𝔫)-action on 𝔫 to Sym 2 (𝔫 *) (38).",
    "Invariant metrics.Let π: M → B be a twisted principal N-bundle.",
    "Recall that there is a welldefined notion of invariance for tensor fields on M (Definition 2.2).",
    "In particular, we may consider invariant Riemannian metrics on M. These have a simple description in terms of the pullback bundle M → B, which is both a principal N-bundle over B, and a principal (π 1 (B) ⋉ ρ N)-bundle over B:Proposition 2.13.",
    "A metric g on M is invariant if and only if its pullback g to M is π 1 (B) ⋉ ρ N-invariant in the usual sense.Proof."
  ]
}